02:44.549 --> 02:47.403
<b>5x02 - ... Goodbye</b>

02:52.769 --> 02:55.638
[sighs]

03:01.144 --> 03:02.846
Good morning.

03:03.613 --> 03:05.614
What are you doing here?

03:07.451 --> 03:09.919
I have dealt with hundreds of homicides

03:09.953 --> 03:11.787
and the grieving relatives
that go with them.

03:11.855 --> 03:13.189
- I can deal with this.
- Really?

03:13.223 --> 03:15.791
Because you had coffee
in your pencil holder.

03:15.859 --> 03:18.094
It's not a pencil holder.
Maura was messing with me.

03:18.128 --> 03:21.764
- Go home.
- [sighs] No.

03:21.798 --> 03:23.799
Maybe I wasn't clear.
I'm ordering you to go home.

03:23.834 --> 03:25.634
- You're ordering me?
- Yes.

03:25.669 --> 03:27.436
We don't have a case we're working on.

03:27.471 --> 03:29.071
I'm the sergeant
detective of this squad.

03:29.106 --> 03:31.032
- I have the authority to send you home.
- Oh, if you think I'm gonna

03:31.189 --> 03:32.217
- If I think you're not ...
- let you pull rank on me,

03:32.401 --> 03:34.293
- it's not ...
- Jane?

03:34.611 --> 03:36.045
Mrs. Frost.

03:36.079 --> 03:39.171
[sniffles] I'm sorry to interrupt.
[voice breaking] I...

03:39.172 --> 03:43.605
- I just didn't know where else to go.
- [sniffling] Uh... okay...

03:44.971 --> 03:47.072
[crying]

03:47.107 --> 03:49.875
I'm so sorry.

03:52.145 --> 03:55.335
<i>And then the funeral
director started asking me</i>

03:55.370 --> 03:57.719
all these questions like
did I want a viewing,

03:57.754 --> 03:59.952
should Barry wear his uniform,

03:59.986 --> 04:02.688
<i>what kind of music should they play.</i>

04:02.722 --> 04:05.858
And I realized... I don't know.

04:05.925 --> 04:09.328
- How could you?
- A couple of years ago, Barry sat me down

04:09.396 --> 04:12.731
and had me tell him what
I wanted at my service.

04:12.766 --> 04:15.234
It never dawned on me to ask about his.

04:15.268 --> 04:18.170
[voice breaking] He was just so young.

04:18.204 --> 04:21.874
Would you like us to take
care of the service for you?

04:23.677 --> 04:26.045
[sighs]
I couldn't ask you to do that.

04:26.079 --> 04:28.647
You didn't ask.
I volunteered.

04:28.682 --> 04:31.050
Even his father can't get here.
H-he's on a ship

04:31.051 --> 04:33.919
doing a support mission
in the middle of the Pacific.

04:33.953 --> 04:38.157
So... it would mean so
much if you could help.

04:38.191 --> 04:41.994
We'd be honored.

04:42.028 --> 04:43.996
And of course we'll,
uh, keep you in the loop

04:44.030 --> 04:47.299
- on all the preparations.
- Well...

04:47.334 --> 04:50.135
nobody knew my son
better than you all did,

04:50.170 --> 04:53.465
so whatever you decide,
I know it will be perfect.

04:53.533 --> 04:56.829
Just what Barry would have wanted.

04:59.728 --> 05:03.412
- Well, now you got a reason to go home.
- Vince, come on.

05:03.480 --> 05:05.915
Please don't pull rank on me now, okay?

05:05.949 --> 05:07.550
I know your heart is in the right...

05:10.153 --> 05:11.320
Gun!

05:11.354 --> 05:12.922
[guns cock]
Put your weapon down.

05:12.989 --> 05:14.323
- Put it down.
- Help me.

05:14.357 --> 05:16.992
We'll help you as soon
as you give us that gun.

05:23.300 --> 05:27.236
- What's your name?
- I-I don't know.

05:27.270 --> 05:29.071
Okay.
What kind of help do you need?

05:31.274 --> 05:34.243
[voice breaking] I killed someone.

05:34.277 --> 05:38.080
- Who?
- I don't know that, either.

05:42.152 --> 05:44.283
[handcuffs click]
Well, I guess we got a case now.

05:54.193 --> 05:55.360
How did you get here?

05:55.395 --> 06:02.067
I, um... I walked by
the deli, dry cleaner,

06:02.135 --> 06:06.371
and then I saw a policeman walk
in here, so I-I followed him.

06:06.406 --> 06:11.510
- How about before that?
- I-I don't know.

06:11.544 --> 06:14.312
- What city are we in?
- Boston.

06:14.380 --> 06:18.083
- What's your favorite baseball team?
- Red Sox.

06:18.117 --> 06:20.085
<i>You said you killed someone.</i>

06:20.119 --> 06:22.254
Did that happen in the day or the night?

06:22.288 --> 06:25.090
I-I don't ... I don't know.

06:25.158 --> 06:27.192
[elevator bell dings]

06:29.996 --> 06:33.131
We just need it high enough
so I can remove her clothes in private.

06:34.500 --> 06:37.269
That was very considerate.

06:37.303 --> 06:39.104
I'd hate to have to testify
on why we undressed her

06:39.138 --> 06:40.539
in front of the entire
Boston police force.

06:40.573 --> 06:42.040
<i>Amanda: Doctor?</i>

06:42.075 --> 06:44.101
Uh, after we've collected
the clothing, take

06:44.102 --> 06:46.127
the tarp to evidence
and make sure we process

06:46.193 --> 06:48.246
- everything that fell off.
- Mm-hmm.

06:48.281 --> 06:51.883
Amanda's gonna remove your
clothes and your shoes.

06:51.918 --> 06:54.853
<i>And we have scrubs and
shoes for you to put on.</i>

06:54.887 --> 06:57.089
<i>If you're cold, I can give
you a reflective blanket.</i>

06:57.123 --> 06:58.623
O-okay.

07:04.664 --> 07:07.534
I'm not going home.

07:08.968 --> 07:11.970
Planning a funeral takes a lot of time.

07:12.004 --> 07:14.039
She might have committed
a murder or not.

07:14.073 --> 07:16.007
He would have wanted
me to stay on the job

07:16.042 --> 07:17.309
and figure out what happened.

07:17.343 --> 07:19.311
Have you noticed that
you won't say his name?

07:21.280 --> 07:22.981
Barry Frost.

07:23.015 --> 07:26.284
- There. You happy, Dr. Freud?
- Well, freud actually believed

07:26.319 --> 07:28.653
that everything was related to
some repressed sexual desire.

07:28.688 --> 07:30.489
I do not think that is the reason

07:30.523 --> 07:32.891
that you will not say
Detective Frost's name.

07:32.925 --> 07:35.193
I have to figure out who she is.
I will talk to you later.

07:35.228 --> 07:39.131
Probably shouldn't have said that.

07:39.465 --> 07:41.299
[sighs]
All his years on the force,

07:41.334 --> 07:43.935
he's entitled to the
pomp and circumstance,

07:43.970 --> 07:45.854
even if he didn't die
in the line of duty.

07:45.897 --> 07:49.330
Hey. I heard about Frost.
It's a real shame.

07:49.840 --> 07:55.079
- He was a good man.
- Yeah, he was. Thanks.

07:57.558 --> 07:59.225
Look, I know everybody means well,

07:59.260 --> 08:01.528
but that's gonna be real
tough to do 200 times today.

08:01.562 --> 08:05.198
[sighs] And, yes, of
course he deserves it.

08:05.232 --> 08:08.468
Frost deserves a cop's funeral.

08:08.502 --> 08:11.571
But if we go full pageant,
then it becomes a photo op.

08:11.605 --> 08:14.307
If it becomes a photo op,
then everyone shows up ...

08:14.341 --> 08:18.545
- the Cardinal, the Mayor.
- Frost hated the Mayor.

08:18.579 --> 08:21.614
He wrote in Bill "spaceman" Lee
instead of voting for him.

08:23.117 --> 08:25.952
Exactly.

08:25.986 --> 08:29.489
Let's keep what Frost liked
and ditch what he hated.

08:29.523 --> 08:34.460
So no to the Mayor and...

08:34.495 --> 08:38.565
- yes to bagpipes.
- How did he feel about "Danny boy"?

08:38.599 --> 08:43.203
Yes to bagpipes, no to "Danny boy."
You be in charge of the music.

08:43.236 --> 08:46.472
- I don't know anything about music.
- You want to do the eulogy?

08:47.641 --> 08:50.710
- You're good with music?
- Hey, I volunteered for pictures.

08:50.744 --> 08:52.478
Oh, I'm no good at pictures either.

08:52.513 --> 08:56.052
Well, why don't you just let me know
when you decide what you're least bad at?

08:57.953 --> 08:59.883
Hey Jane. Your woman's
fingerprints are a bust.

08:59.950 --> 09:03.353
She wasn't in the database.
But her gun was recently fired.

09:03.421 --> 09:05.488
Any dead bodies lying in the street

09:05.523 --> 09:07.490
that are in need of
a suspect to go with them?

09:07.525 --> 09:10.394
- Wouldn't that be convenient?
- Well, missing-persons' reports

09:10.395 --> 09:11.261
- matching her description?
- No.

09:11.295 --> 09:13.763
Uninvestigated gunshots
anywhere in the greater

09:13.764 --> 09:14.497
- Boston area?
- Oh, come on.

09:14.565 --> 09:16.416
We all know she's faking
amnesia to set up

09:16.417 --> 09:18.268
a mental-incapacitation
defense for a murder trial.

09:18.302 --> 09:21.455
Probably.
But she was covered in blood

09:21.456 --> 09:22.839
and had no visible injuries.

09:22.873 --> 09:25.041
I mean, based on volume
alone, someone is dead

09:25.076 --> 09:27.911
or going to be soon
if we don't find them.

09:27.945 --> 09:30.347
[beep] No shots. At least
not that shot alert picked up.

09:30.381 --> 09:32.182
Okay. Let's get her
picture to all roll calls,

09:32.216 --> 09:35.085
see if we can track her in
the homeland security cameras.

09:35.119 --> 09:39.889
You all know Roger Wise, the
department grief counselor.

09:39.924 --> 09:42.926
<i>Roger: I was very sorry to
hear about Detective Frost.</i>

09:42.960 --> 09:45.161
I'm here to help any way I can.

09:45.196 --> 09:47.831
So, I can't force any
of you to talk to Roger

09:47.865 --> 09:50.951
about this tragic auto accident.
But I can force you to sit

09:50.952 --> 09:53.503
with him for 30 minutes,
talk about anything you like.

09:53.537 --> 09:57.574
- So, who's first?
- I-I got to distribute the photo.

09:57.608 --> 10:02.512
- I got to check out the cameras.
- I'll, uh...

10:02.546 --> 10:04.948
Thanks for volunteering, detective.

10:05.015 --> 10:08.118
Takes a strong man to
open up about his feelings.

10:13.290 --> 10:17.327
Dr. Maura Isles initiating
the examination of...

10:17.361 --> 10:20.430
I-I don't want to call you "Jane Doe"

10:20.464 --> 10:22.432
because that's what
I call the other women

10:22.466 --> 10:27.370
who end up on this table who are...
less alive than you.

10:27.405 --> 10:30.974
So, based on the
flounce hem of your skirt

10:31.008 --> 10:34.310
and the elasticity of your skin,
I'd say you're in your mid-20s.

10:34.345 --> 10:38.114
The most popular baby name
25 years ago was Jessica.

10:38.149 --> 10:39.983
Okay. [beep]

10:40.017 --> 10:41.518
Maura Isles initiating the examination

10:41.585 --> 10:46.990
of Jessica Doe, female caucasian.
Approximate age is 25.

10:47.057 --> 10:49.426
I'm sorry to be talking
as if you weren't here.

10:49.460 --> 10:52.896
It's okay.
You're trying to help me, right?

10:52.930 --> 10:55.532
Uh, well, I'm ...

10:55.566 --> 10:58.868
I'm trying to find out
what happened to you.

10:58.936 --> 11:00.437
I'm going to take
scrapings to see if there's

11:00.471 --> 11:02.505
any tissues underneath your fingernails.

11:05.075 --> 11:09.245
- So, you like the Red Sox?
- Yeah.

11:09.280 --> 11:12.882
- Do you have a favorite player?
- Dustin Pedroia.

11:12.917 --> 11:15.418
Most defensive runs saved at his
position over the last three years.

11:15.453 --> 11:19.355
- He's got a nice smile.
- Yes, he does.

11:21.492 --> 11:26.429
When I was at BCU,
my roommate took me to a game,

11:26.464 --> 11:29.132
and it was the best hot dog I ever had.

11:29.166 --> 11:33.903
- It's the mustard.
- I didn't know that.

11:33.938 --> 11:37.607
Been to a game recently?

11:42.613 --> 11:45.315
[voice breaking] I don't know.

11:47.051 --> 11:51.521
It's okay.
I am going to floss your teeth.

11:51.589 --> 11:54.324
If you could just open
your mouth for me, please.

11:56.994 --> 11:59.295
I wonder what's in that mustard.

11:59.330 --> 12:01.698
Camera tracks her down
Tremont to Columbus.

12:01.732 --> 12:04.567
Then she heads onto the bike
path, Southwest corridor,

12:04.602 --> 12:06.569
and that's it 'cause the cameras stop.

12:06.604 --> 12:10.139
Okay. Well, I got a hit
on the gun registration.

12:10.174 --> 12:11.441
The owner reported it
stolen three years ago

12:11.509 --> 12:13.443
<i>and doesn't know our woman.</i>

12:13.511 --> 12:16.112
I finished my live autopsy.

12:16.146 --> 12:17.714
Well, technically it can't be
an autopsy because that is,

12:17.748 --> 12:20.149
by definition, an examination
of a body after death.

12:20.184 --> 12:23.319
Although I could be using the
word in the spirit of autopsia,

12:23.387 --> 12:25.922
from the Greek, meaning
"to see with one's own eyes..."

12:27.091 --> 12:29.659
- Anyway. Jessica ...
- Who's Jessica?

12:29.693 --> 12:31.361
The woman from the lobby.

12:31.428 --> 12:33.730
Oh, no, Korsak.
Maura's named her.

12:33.797 --> 12:35.665
Now we'll never be
able to give her back.

12:35.699 --> 12:37.467
<i>Maura: The blood on her clothes
was from a single subject,</i>

12:37.501 --> 12:41.337
- likely male, type A-negative.
- Okay. Probably caucasian.

12:41.372 --> 12:44.438
- Uh, in Boston, yes.
- And in Honolulu?

12:44.512 --> 12:48.111
Well, over a 60% chance that
the subject would be Polynesian.

12:48.145 --> 12:49.112
Do you make this stuff up 'cause

12:49.113 --> 12:51.447
- you know we can't check it?
- Yes.

12:51.482 --> 12:53.550
No. I'm not that fanciful.

12:53.584 --> 12:58.154
Uh, Jessica also had traces
of methylenedioxy on her skirt.

12:58.188 --> 13:01.090
Perfect, that narrows our search down
to 2,000 ecstasy dealers

13:01.125 --> 13:02.625
<i>and about a bajillion ecstasy users.</i>

13:02.693 --> 13:06.629
Oh, I also have a possible
explanation for her amnesia.

13:06.697 --> 13:10.099
She might be in a
dissociative fugue state.

13:10.134 --> 13:13.369
Is that Greek for "faking it?"
'Cause that's what we think right now.

13:13.404 --> 13:15.772
A fugue state is a very
rare condition that occurs

13:15.839 --> 13:18.274
when someone experiences
a trauma so severe

13:18.309 --> 13:20.777
that they block parts of their
consciousness related to it.

13:20.811 --> 13:25.081
A bad thing happens and they forget
anything that might remind

13:25.082 --> 13:26.516
- them of the bad thing.
- Yes.

13:26.550 --> 13:28.217
Jessica doesn't remember who she is

13:28.285 --> 13:31.421
<i>because it's directly connected
to the traumatic event.</i>

13:31.455 --> 13:33.122
But she remembers that
she likes the Red Sox

13:33.157 --> 13:36.859
because it's not.
Oh. There's my vase.

13:41.565 --> 13:43.666
Okay, assuming

13:43.701 --> 13:45.268
we thought this was real ...
which we do not ...

13:45.302 --> 13:46.603
how do we get her to snap out of it?

13:46.637 --> 13:48.771
I would suggest taking
her to familiar places

13:48.806 --> 13:51.140
and seeing if anything
triggers any memories.

13:51.175 --> 13:53.676
Great plan, but because of
her probably fake amnesia,

13:53.711 --> 13:55.044
we don't know anything about her.

13:55.079 --> 14:00.183
Uh, well, she did have
a firstpark ticket in her pocket

14:00.217 --> 14:03.319
and candy-coated fennel
seed in her teeth.

14:03.387 --> 14:06.789
Those are digestives often
found in Indian restaurants.

14:06.857 --> 14:08.591
So firstpark garages
near Indian restaurants.

14:08.626 --> 14:10.593
Does the phrase "wild goose chase"
mean anything to you?

14:10.628 --> 14:14.163
Yes, but...

14:14.198 --> 14:17.700
at least we get to try delicious
digestives all over the city.

14:17.735 --> 14:20.803
- Bye, Maura.
- Bye, Jane.

14:25.409 --> 14:28.244
All right. How about that?
It's called Taste of Tandoor.

14:28.278 --> 14:32.348
- No.
- How many stops do we have left?

14:32.383 --> 14:35.485
Two.
The next restaurant is on Emerson.

14:35.552 --> 14:37.286
Firstpark garage is around the corner.

14:37.321 --> 14:39.622
Oh. What do we do when
those turn up nothing?

14:39.657 --> 14:43.159
Call dispatch, have them put
her picture up on the website.

14:43.227 --> 14:45.361
Nothing? None of this
looks familiar to you?

14:45.429 --> 14:48.130
No. I'm sorry.

14:48.165 --> 14:49.799
Y-you had to have been
to at least one of these places.

14:49.833 --> 14:51.634
I mean, what about Abe & Louie's?

14:51.669 --> 14:53.336
Everybody in Boston's eaten there.

14:53.370 --> 14:56.272
No. Over there.
Across the street.

15:00.944 --> 15:02.779
Wait. Korsak, stop.

15:02.813 --> 15:04.647
Stop! Stop the car!
[tires screech]

15:06.917 --> 15:09.619
[horn honks]
[tires screech]

15:09.653 --> 15:12.188
<i>Woman: Oh, my gosh!
Look out for that car!</i>

15:12.222 --> 15:13.856
[horn honks]
[tires screech]

15:13.924 --> 15:15.376
<i>Man: What?! Are you crazy?!</i>

15:27.095 --> 15:28.929
[horn honks]

15:31.998 --> 15:34.201
Thanks.

15:34.235 --> 15:36.924
- I feel so stupid.
- No need.

15:37.505 --> 15:39.106
It just seemed so real.

15:39.140 --> 15:42.743
I mean, I could have sworn
he was standing right there.

15:42.777 --> 15:45.145
At the beginning of my career,

15:45.179 --> 15:47.147
I was first on the scene
at an auto accident.

15:47.181 --> 15:48.982
Older guy ran into a telephone pole.

15:49.016 --> 15:50.751
The M.E. at the time
thought he might have

15:50.785 --> 15:52.252
had a heart attack
and died at the wheel.

15:52.286 --> 15:55.188
And the man had a smile on his face

15:55.223 --> 15:57.157
like he died without
a care in the world.

15:57.191 --> 16:02.262
For months after that,
I saw the guy all over Boston ...

16:02.296 --> 16:04.898
sitting on a park bench,
once at Fenway Park.

16:04.932 --> 16:07.267
Did that really happen
or are you just telling me

16:07.268 --> 16:07.968
that to make me feel better?

16:08.002 --> 16:10.937
I swear to god. The
mind does funny things.

16:10.972 --> 16:13.106
Do you think Frost made us stop?

16:13.141 --> 16:14.875
Uh, I don't believe
in that stuff. Do you?

16:14.909 --> 16:16.260
No, but I think if I were dead

16:16.261 --> 16:20.046
and you were here with Frost,
he might have believed it.

16:21.182 --> 16:23.650
I mean, if she's running a con,

16:23.684 --> 16:25.919
does she actually think
she's gonna get away with it?

16:25.953 --> 16:27.921
I've said it before.

16:27.955 --> 16:30.891
Criminals are generally
very, very stupid.

16:30.958 --> 16:34.094
[horn honks]

16:41.302 --> 16:43.270
Okay, listen.

16:43.304 --> 16:45.872
I want to believe that what
you're saying is real ...

16:45.907 --> 16:47.507
that you don't remember
who you are, all right?

16:47.542 --> 16:49.509
And most days, I wouldn't
be able to do that.

16:49.544 --> 16:51.678
- But today I'm gonna try, okay?
- # Go 'round and 'round #

16:51.712 --> 16:53.647
- But if you don't remember something...
- # 'round and 'round #

16:53.681 --> 16:55.148
- ...I can't help you.
- # 'round and 'round #

16:55.183 --> 16:58.652
♪ the wheels on the bus
go 'round and 'round ♪

16:58.686 --> 17:00.654
♪ 'round and 'round ♪

17:00.688 --> 17:02.222
♪ 'round and 'round ♪

17:02.256 --> 17:06.059
♪ the wheels on the bus
go 'round and 'round ♪

17:06.093 --> 17:08.161
♪ all through the town ♪

17:08.195 --> 17:10.696
Whoa. Whoa, whoa. What?
D-do you have children?

17:10.731 --> 17:13.066
I-I don't think so.

17:13.099 --> 17:16.002
Okay. Uh, does it have
something to do with kids?

17:17.305 --> 17:18.905
Are you a teacher?

17:20.340 --> 17:26.946
- Yes! [chuckles]
- Okay. Okay.

17:28.348 --> 17:30.750
Maybe he's helping us
solve this after all.

17:39.060 --> 17:42.175
- Any luck?
- It would help if teachers

17:42.176 --> 17:44.197
in Massachusetts had
fingerprints on file.

17:44.198 --> 17:45.298
I'll hop in my time machine

17:45.366 --> 17:47.200
and go back and let the
Union know your preference.

17:47.235 --> 17:51.071
W-without a name, I'm having
to call up individual schools.

17:51.105 --> 17:53.073
And I'm making a list
of absent teachers.

17:53.107 --> 17:55.242
And I'm pulling up
footage from schools nearby

17:55.276 --> 17:57.277
to see if she wandered
out of one of them.

17:57.311 --> 17:59.145
[groans]

17:59.180 --> 18:00.981
It's gonna take a
while to finish it all.

18:01.015 --> 18:04.751
I get it. Fingerprints on
file would be a lot easier.

18:04.785 --> 18:07.888
- Where's Jane?
- It was a long day. I sent her home.

18:07.922 --> 18:09.990
And she listened?
[chuckles]

18:10.057 --> 18:12.993
I suppose it's possible she's
sitting downstairs in the lobby.

18:14.662 --> 18:17.163
How's it coming with the
music for the funeral?

18:17.198 --> 18:20.834
Oh, I've eliminated many, many choices.

18:20.868 --> 18:22.836
- So nowhere.
- [chuckling] Basically.

18:22.870 --> 18:23.870
Hmm.

18:23.938 --> 18:27.140
[chuckles]

18:28.976 --> 18:32.045
- Lunch sucked today.
- What did you do?

18:32.079 --> 18:35.649
[sighs] I sat at my desk and...

18:35.683 --> 18:38.919
wondered where Frost
would have wanted to go.

18:38.953 --> 18:41.154
What did you decide?

18:43.391 --> 18:46.359
[voice breaking]
I ... I wasn't hungry.

18:48.229 --> 18:49.362
Hmm.

18:50.932 --> 18:53.667
Oh, hell.

18:57.305 --> 19:00.006
[knock on door] I'm headed home.

19:00.041 --> 19:02.742
Well, you're welcome to spend
the night again if you'd like.

19:02.777 --> 19:04.144
No, thanks. I'd rather be alone.

19:08.816 --> 19:13.053
- No offense.
- None taken. How are you holding up?

19:13.120 --> 19:15.188
[sighs]

19:15.222 --> 19:19.059
- I'm tired.
- Well, the development of the placenta

19:19.126 --> 19:20.827
is one of the most
energetically intense parts

19:20.861 --> 19:22.963
of the first trimester ...
that could be the reason.

19:22.997 --> 19:25.231
Or it could be that one of
my best friends just died.

19:25.966 --> 19:28.401
Yes. That could be it, too.

19:28.469 --> 19:32.706
- I saw him on the street today.
- I'm sorry?

19:32.740 --> 19:36.943
I mean, I didn't. [stammers]
I thought I saw him on the street today.

19:36.978 --> 19:39.245
That's called an anomalous experience.

19:39.280 --> 19:43.850
It's ... it's perfectly normal.
As is crying.

19:43.884 --> 19:45.852
How do you know I haven't cried yet?

19:45.886 --> 19:47.954
Because you would have
said, "I had a good cry

19:48.022 --> 19:49.789
and it didn't help,"
or something like that.

19:49.857 --> 19:52.092
How are you doing?

19:52.126 --> 19:54.094
I think I've moved
through denial and anger.

19:54.128 --> 19:56.363
I'm ready to move into bargaining

19:56.430 --> 19:58.164
and I'll have a good cry
when I get to depression.

19:58.199 --> 20:00.700
- Can't plan a cry, Maura.
- I'm not planning it.

20:00.735 --> 20:03.403
I'm just narrowing down
the window of its arrival.

20:03.437 --> 20:05.839
And it occurred to me today that ...

20:05.873 --> 20:08.375
that we need to talk
about our last wishes.

20:08.409 --> 20:11.478
- No, we don't.
- I want to be buried at sea.

20:11.512 --> 20:13.119
No. I hate boats.

20:13.120 --> 20:17.422
And I'd have to go to city hall
and get all kinds of permits and...

20:17.423 --> 20:20.134
no, just pick something more landlocked.

20:20.135 --> 20:24.497
Jane, I want to return to the
primordial soup that spawned us all.

20:24.532 --> 20:27.753
But nothing fancy ... a small group
of friends and family, a cello.

20:27.836 --> 20:31.826
We're on a boat, Maura.
And a cello is officially fancy.

20:31.936 --> 20:33.315
Well, there would only be one.

20:33.398 --> 20:36.359
And it should play
Bach's suite in "G" major.

20:36.769 --> 20:38.774
And then everyone can
toast me with a nice

20:38.775 --> 20:40.780
bottle of champagne before
you throw me overboard.

20:40.848 --> 20:45.365
- So, what do you want?
- I want to die one day before you

20:45.436 --> 20:48.555
so I don't have to go out on a boat.

20:48.589 --> 20:49.823
[elevator bell dings]

20:51.926 --> 20:53.226
I'll see you tomorrow.

20:54.829 --> 20:56.696
[chuckles]

21:03.404 --> 21:05.372
Hey, Ma.
What are you doing here?

21:05.406 --> 21:07.040
Making dinner.

21:07.074 --> 21:11.244
I really appreciate it,
but, uh, I'm not that hungry.

21:11.279 --> 21:13.480
Then you'll eat just a little bit.

21:13.548 --> 21:15.081
I just want to go to bed, Ma.

21:15.116 --> 21:18.385
You got to eat, Jane.
Even if you're sad.

21:20.121 --> 21:21.621
Come on.

21:26.394 --> 21:28.395
[sighs]

21:37.405 --> 21:41.174
- Why are you still here?
- For Jane.

21:41.209 --> 21:42.475
Yeah, I figured the
more progress we make,

21:42.510 --> 21:43.743
the less she'll have
to worry about the case.

21:43.778 --> 21:46.279
- What about you?
- Same thing.

21:46.314 --> 21:47.681
Come on! Please?

21:47.748 --> 21:49.983
Okay, well, t-the next time
you ask me for a favor...

21:50.017 --> 21:54.254
I'll... probably help you
out because I'm a decent guy.

21:54.322 --> 21:58.058
- But I will not be nice about it!
- What's going on?

21:58.092 --> 22:00.360
Well, we didn't get anywhere
with the local teachers' unions.

22:00.394 --> 22:01.695
And then it dawns on me.

22:01.729 --> 22:04.564
Maybe our woman doesn't
work in the public school.

22:04.599 --> 22:07.534
So I called a bunch of private schools
near Indian restaurants.

22:07.568 --> 22:10.270
- You know who she is?
- Lily Greene.

22:10.304 --> 22:13.773
Uh, she teaches at Red Tree preschool.

22:13.808 --> 22:16.109
Only I can't find a judge
to sign a search warrant.

22:16.143 --> 22:19.746
I walked in at the right moment.
That just happens to be my specialty.

22:24.168 --> 22:25.836
Good night.

22:26.220 --> 22:27.454
Have a good shift, Todd.

22:27.488 --> 22:30.156
Oh, you have a nice evening, too.
Uh, Dr. Isles?

22:30.191 --> 22:32.058
I-I heard about Detective Frost.

22:32.093 --> 22:34.527
I'm sorry. I know the
two of you were close.

22:34.562 --> 22:36.796
Thank you, Todd.

22:36.831 --> 22:40.200
He was a nice guy ...
a-a really nice guy.

22:41.702 --> 22:44.671
Yes. He was.

22:55.250 --> 22:57.451
[sniffles]

22:58.386 --> 23:01.254
[sobbing]

23:19.755 --> 23:20.755
[knocking]

23:20.756 --> 23:22.657
- Good morning.
- Shh!

23:22.691 --> 23:24.258
What?

23:24.292 --> 23:27.328
<i>- Oh. What is she doing here?
- Watching me.</i>

23:39.244 --> 23:43.481
Before we go to the station,
can we stop and get some breakfast?

23:43.549 --> 23:46.184
We're not going to the station.
We're going to Lily Greene's apartment.

23:46.218 --> 23:49.454
Oh. I'm so hungry.
Who's Lily Greene?

23:49.488 --> 23:52.023
You know, miss "I have blood all over me
and I don't know who I am."

23:52.057 --> 23:53.291
So you found out who
she is. That's great.

23:53.325 --> 23:56.027
- What did she say when you told her?
- Well, we haven't told her yet.

23:56.061 --> 23:57.295
I mean, we've got one
shot at a confession.

23:57.329 --> 23:59.764
So if we open the door to
her apartment and there's

23:59.765 --> 24:02.200
a dead body in there, it kind
of makes it a little difficult

24:02.234 --> 24:04.202
for her to keep faking amnesia ...

24:04.236 --> 24:08.272
- if that's what she's doing.
- Okay, so crime scene, then breakfast.

24:08.307 --> 24:10.408
Why didn't you eat a muffin
before you left the house?

24:10.442 --> 24:12.143
There's no nutrition in a muffin.

24:15.981 --> 24:19.217
There's no nutrition in gum.

24:19.251 --> 24:21.347
<i>Well, I like juicy fruit.</i>

24:36.268 --> 24:39.270
- Clear.
- Clear.

24:39.304 --> 24:42.507
- Can I come in now?
- Yeah.

24:42.574 --> 24:45.543
Just seems that we're one body
short of an actual crime scene.

24:45.577 --> 24:46.644
Well, there's been a crime.

24:46.678 --> 24:51.415
- Just not one requiring an autopsy.
- It's a very thorough search.

24:51.450 --> 24:53.050
Yeah, which begs the question,
what were they looking for?

24:53.085 --> 24:57.288
Found some money wrappers.
About $2,000 worth.

24:57.322 --> 25:00.291
I can fast-track them for drug residue.

25:04.196 --> 25:08.933
Looks like there's a Mr. Lily Greene.

25:08.967 --> 25:12.069
<i>Frankie: I pulled up her cellphone
records as soon as we got the warrant.</i>

25:12.104 --> 25:16.440
She made a lot of calls
to a guy named Toby Warren.

25:19.077 --> 25:21.012
Okay.
Let's get a warrant out for him, too.

25:29.187 --> 25:30.521
[grunts]

25:30.556 --> 25:33.958
Thanks.

25:35.661 --> 25:40.031
Barista gave me the usual.
I didn't have the heart to give it back.

25:40.065 --> 25:43.534
- What are you doing?
- Um...

25:43.569 --> 25:46.037
the part of the job that
Frost would normally do

25:46.071 --> 25:47.939
and a lot slower than
he would normally do it.

25:48.006 --> 25:50.608
So far, Lily Greene seems
like a stand-up citizen.

25:50.642 --> 25:52.610
There's not even a parking ticket.

25:52.644 --> 25:55.580
And all I got on Toby
Warren is that he's been

25:55.614 --> 25:57.949
collecting unemployment
for the past 18 months.

25:57.983 --> 26:01.018
Maybe she got tired of supporting him.
He trashed the apartment

26:01.053 --> 26:02.320
looking for extra money
to soften his landing.

26:02.354 --> 26:04.555
She tracked him down,
ended the relationship.

26:04.590 --> 26:07.992
I feel sorry for Kiki if this is how
you think you should end a relationship.

26:08.026 --> 26:10.728
I'm not dating Kiki.
She's my life coach.

26:14.466 --> 26:18.436
How about I take over... "that"
and you go get some fresh air?

26:18.470 --> 26:20.538
I can keep hitting the button.

26:20.572 --> 26:23.407
That's probably a good idea.

26:27.412 --> 26:29.923
<i>My condolences.</i>

26:31.882 --> 26:34.818
- Hi.
- Hi.

26:35.810 --> 26:38.378
How are you doing?

26:38.412 --> 26:42.615
If I get up at the funeral
and just say nothing,

26:42.650 --> 26:44.250
will you nod your head

26:44.285 --> 26:46.586
like I'm doing something
deep and meaningful?

26:46.620 --> 26:49.656
I absolutely will.

26:51.425 --> 26:53.393
Did you find anything at
Toby Warren's apartment?

26:53.427 --> 26:55.362
Not Toby Warren, if
that's what you mean.

26:55.396 --> 26:58.893
You have a "but" to go along
with that unhelpful information?

26:59.013 --> 27:02.369
His cellphone's been pinging
off the same tower for 24 hours.

27:02.436 --> 27:05.672
I had his service
provider turn on his GPS.

27:05.740 --> 27:07.607
Is that your way of telling
me to get off my ass?

27:07.641 --> 27:09.876
[clears throat]

27:11.479 --> 27:13.948
Come on.

27:14.732 --> 27:17.667
[guns cock]

27:42.326 --> 27:43.627
[camera shutter clicking]

27:43.694 --> 27:46.563
We got one bullet
embedded in the wood here.

27:46.631 --> 27:49.065
Hey, Frankie. Our gun may
have been discharged twice.

27:49.100 --> 27:50.200
Let's see if we can
find that other bullet.

27:50.268 --> 27:52.636
- Will do.
- Thanks.

27:52.670 --> 27:55.071
Based on this wound and that bullet,

27:55.106 --> 27:58.175
- he was kneeling when he died.
- It's an execution.

27:58.209 --> 28:01.178
So, the bullet entered
in his parietal bone

28:01.245 --> 28:03.180
<i>right above the lambdoid suture</i>

28:03.247 --> 28:05.248
<i>and it exited through the
right common carotid artery.</i>

28:05.283 --> 28:10.086
In order for her to be
covered in arterial spray

28:10.121 --> 28:13.423
- on that part of her clothes...
- She'd had to have been kneeling

28:13.491 --> 28:15.859
right next to him when he was shot.

28:15.893 --> 28:18.228
That's certainly something
I'd want to forget.

28:18.262 --> 28:21.631
But to create that angle
and this entry wound,

28:21.699 --> 28:26.536
the bullet fired at at least
15 degrees from perpendicular

28:26.571 --> 28:29.105
and at a distance of
greater than 18 inches.

28:29.140 --> 28:31.474
Mm-hmm, so that means
she would have to shoot

28:31.509 --> 28:35.812
across his body.
That can't be done.

28:35.847 --> 28:37.781
No. Not unless her
arms are four feet long.

28:37.815 --> 28:41.484
So, either she's Elastigirl
or Lily Greene didn't kill Toby Warren.

28:41.519 --> 28:44.621
Well, I'm gonna go out on a limb
and eliminate your Elastigirl theory.

28:44.655 --> 28:47.157
Hey, doc? I got a round
blood drop on the floor here.

28:47.191 --> 28:48.792
And no way that's splatter
from Toby Warren, right?

28:48.826 --> 28:50.760
That definitely didn't
come from Toby's wounds.

28:50.795 --> 28:53.396
I don't know where the second bullet is,
but it looks like it hit someone.

28:53.431 --> 28:57.234
Well, what if the tissue that you found
under Lily's fingernails

28:57.268 --> 28:59.236
were from her fighting the killer?

28:59.270 --> 29:01.404
It could be that's how
she ended up with the gun.

29:01.439 --> 29:04.474
Jane, this one's smeared.
Looks like they stepped in it.

29:04.508 --> 29:07.444
Judging from the stride,
looks like they were running.

29:07.478 --> 29:11.448
Okay. So...
someone shoots Toby.

29:11.482 --> 29:13.550
Lily ends up with the gun,
shoots that person,

29:13.618 --> 29:15.151
and he or she runs away.

29:15.186 --> 29:17.387
Those are the facts as
we currently know them.

29:17.455 --> 29:19.439
Just because Lily didn't
shoot Toby doesn't mean

29:19.440 --> 29:21.424
she wasn't involved in
whatever got him shot.

29:21.492 --> 29:23.560
- Is that your gut?
- No.

29:23.594 --> 29:28.498
No, my gut says that whoever
ran away is our killer

29:28.499 --> 29:32.435
and that Lily Greene is
a completely innocent schoolteacher

29:32.470 --> 29:35.071
who just had the worst
night of her life.

29:41.279 --> 29:43.680
Would you like a cup of coffee?

29:43.714 --> 29:46.416
It won't taste very good, but it'll be warm.

29:46.451 --> 29:49.319
No, thank you.
Did you find out who I am?

29:49.353 --> 29:52.289
We did.
Your name is Lily Greene.

29:52.323 --> 29:54.091
Um, you're a preschool teacher.

29:55.860 --> 29:57.694
Does any of that sound familiar?

29:57.728 --> 30:01.431
- Not really.
- Okay.

30:01.466 --> 30:04.267
We think we have an idea
of what happened to you.

30:04.302 --> 30:05.802
You do?

30:09.040 --> 30:13.421
Lily...
do you recognize this man?

30:14.045 --> 30:16.813
<i>Toby: No, I s-swear I'll make this right.</i>

30:16.881 --> 30:18.348
<i>If you just give me a chance.
I promise.</i>

30:18.382 --> 30:21.251
<i>I'll do anything.
It won't happen again.</i>

30:21.285 --> 30:22.786
<i>I didn't think ...
I mean, I didn't know.</i>

30:22.820 --> 30:24.454
<i>[gunshot]
[screams]</i>

30:24.489 --> 30:28.258
- No. No, no, no. No.
- Okay. I-I know this is hard.

30:28.292 --> 30:33.230
- I don't want to talk anymore.
- Lily... you're safe.

30:33.264 --> 30:36.333
Whatever happened, you're safe now.

30:36.367 --> 30:37.801
And pretending that it didn't happen ...

30:37.835 --> 30:40.837
it's not gonna change anything.

30:47.044 --> 30:51.148
<i>Toby: Please!
Don't. I swear I'll fix this.</i>

30:51.182 --> 30:53.783
<i>I can. If you just give
me a chance, I promise.</i>

30:55.987 --> 30:57.487
Toby.

30:59.323 --> 31:01.391
I'm so sorry, sweetie. He's dead.

31:01.459 --> 31:04.027
[sobs]

31:08.332 --> 31:11.001
Tell me what you remember.

31:11.035 --> 31:15.005
[voice breaking]
No, he was a good man.

31:15.039 --> 31:17.040
I think he just lost his way, you know?

31:17.074 --> 31:20.477
I do.
I do. What happened?

31:20.511 --> 31:23.079
A couple nights ago, Toby told me

31:23.114 --> 31:25.081
that in college he used to sell drugs

31:25.116 --> 31:27.450
and that he started again
when he lost his job.

31:27.485 --> 31:30.954
<i>He needed to pay his bills
so he took some money.</i>

31:30.988 --> 31:34.224
And the man he was
dealing for found out,

31:34.258 --> 31:37.027
said he had to give it back.

31:37.061 --> 31:42.165
<i>Toby told me he was in trouble.
I lent him everything I had.</i>

31:42.233 --> 31:44.801
It wasn't all he owed, but we thought,

31:44.835 --> 31:49.206
you know, if we just
showed good faith...

31:49.240 --> 31:52.475
but... it didn't matter.

31:52.510 --> 31:56.413
We'll make him pay for this, Lily.
Just help me find him.

31:57.480 --> 32:03.153
His name is Kyle.
That's all I know.

32:03.187 --> 32:05.322
That's enough.

32:05.356 --> 32:08.291
[crying]

32:08.359 --> 32:11.861
We'll find him. I promise.

32:11.896 --> 32:13.396
[elevator bell dings]

32:17.001 --> 32:21.371
Hi. Did you pick out
music for the funeral yet?

32:21.405 --> 32:23.940
I got it narrowed down
to about 20 choices.

32:23.975 --> 32:26.042
Which is only slightly
better than no choices.

32:26.110 --> 32:28.478
- Where are you with the pictures?
- Done.

32:28.512 --> 32:31.348
Did you know that he had
a wall full of albums?

32:31.415 --> 32:33.116
Guy loved music. Makes
sense he'd have a lot of CDs.

32:33.150 --> 32:37.854
Not CDs.
Vinyl.

32:37.888 --> 32:41.157
It was on the turntable.
It's probably the thing he listened to

32:41.192 --> 32:45.228
before he left on vacation.
Thought it might help you out.

32:45.296 --> 32:47.830
Detective Frost had good taste.

32:48.666 --> 32:53.203
[voice breaking] And just like that,
I've narrowed my choices down to one.

32:53.237 --> 32:55.238
Thanks, Frankie.

33:00.210 --> 33:03.413
Frankie, you sure this is a solid lead?

33:03.447 --> 33:06.883
<i>Everybody going in and out of this place
looks more moonshine than ecstasy.</i>

33:06.917 --> 33:09.286
The drugs guys don't know
Kyle, but they've heard his name

33:09.320 --> 33:12.155
and they say this is where most of
the ecstasy in Boston passes through.

33:12.189 --> 33:13.256
<i>Korsak: Why haven't
they moved on it yet?</i>

33:13.291 --> 33:14.858
Oh, the usual reason.

33:14.925 --> 33:17.160
<i>Waiting for bigger fish to swim by.</i>

33:17.194 --> 33:21.116
[rustling] Are you
searching through my car?

33:21.151 --> 33:22.098
<i>No.</i>

33:22.133 --> 33:23.400
Was he this annoying as a kid?

33:23.434 --> 33:26.236
- So much more so.
- I can hear you!

33:26.271 --> 33:28.171
[cellphone beeps]

33:30.007 --> 33:31.107
Are you ready?

33:31.375 --> 33:34.576
You mean the funeral?

33:34.611 --> 33:36.179
[sighs]

33:36.213 --> 33:39.215
My mom took the food because she said
she knew what Frost would want.

33:39.250 --> 33:40.284
Maura took the flowers

33:40.285 --> 33:42.352
'cause she said none of us
knew anything about flowers.

33:42.386 --> 33:43.920
You say you're good with the music.

33:43.988 --> 33:46.589
His mom got the minister. I ...

33:46.624 --> 33:48.458
I got nothing.

33:48.492 --> 33:51.194
Every time I think about
the eulogy, I just...

33:51.228 --> 33:54.931
all I picture is Frost laughing at me.
It ... it ...

33:54.965 --> 33:57.000
it really messes with my
concentration, you know? It...

33:57.034 --> 33:59.336
Maybe you just need to have
a good cry, loosen yourself up.

33:59.370 --> 34:01.037
I really wish that all of you ...

34:01.072 --> 34:03.319
<i>Is that him?</i>

34:07.425 --> 34:08.344
Yep.

34:08.379 --> 34:11.281
<i>Korsak: Frankie, that's our guy.</i>

34:11.315 --> 34:13.983
<i>- So we can't take him out until we're away from here.
- Jane: Yeah, we know.</i>

34:14.018 --> 34:16.960
And you make sure you put Korsak's
candy back in its hiding place.

34:16.995 --> 34:19.556
- I didn't find any candy.
- I don't have candy.

34:19.623 --> 34:22.737
[engine turns over]
[tires squeal]

34:23.494 --> 34:26.196
[tires screech]

34:27.476 --> 34:29.065
Let me see your hands!

34:29.132 --> 34:30.166
[gun cocks]

34:30.234 --> 34:33.636
<i>- Shoot.
- Here!</i>

34:36.741 --> 34:38.341
Stop!

34:40.378 --> 34:41.543
[gun cocks]
Freeze!

34:51.260 --> 34:54.362
[laughs] Look at that.

34:54.397 --> 34:56.931
I bet that matches the skin we found
under Lily Greene's fingernails.

34:56.966 --> 34:58.400
Congratulations, Kyle.

34:58.434 --> 35:00.890
You're under arrest for
the murder of Toby Warren.

35:09.472 --> 35:10.839
[elevator bell dings]

35:10.874 --> 35:13.075
The front desk said that

35:13.109 --> 35:16.912
your father was down
here waiting for you.

35:16.946 --> 35:19.848
<i>Lily: Dad.</i>

35:31.561 --> 35:33.562
Wait. Detective Rizzoli.

35:33.596 --> 35:35.731
[sighs]

35:35.765 --> 35:39.535
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

35:39.569 --> 35:40.836
You know, if you hadn't worked so hard,

35:40.870 --> 35:46.141
- I would have never remembered.
- I'm very sorry for your loss.

35:47.175 --> 35:51.085
I'm very sorry for yours.

35:51.533 --> 35:56.227
[bagpipes play "Amazing grace"]

36:35.810 --> 36:38.046
[sighs]

36:38.080 --> 36:39.547
Um...

36:39.581 --> 36:43.217
we shouldn't be here today.

36:45.554 --> 36:48.523
Barry Frost was too young

36:48.557 --> 36:52.760
and too good for us to be here today.

36:52.828 --> 36:55.096
But yet, here we are.

36:55.130 --> 36:58.533
<i>I've been given the incredible honor</i>

36:58.567 --> 37:00.635
<i>of talking about how
much we all loved Barry.</i>

37:00.703 --> 37:03.504
<i>And I could say "a lot" and go sit down,</i>

37:03.539 --> 37:05.173
but it wouldn't do him justice.

37:05.207 --> 37:06.941
[door opens]

37:09.945 --> 37:11.045
Barry was...

37:11.113 --> 37:12.513
[door closes]

37:12.581 --> 37:15.083
...so many things to so many people.

37:15.150 --> 37:18.119
Um...

37:20.889 --> 37:22.623
a son...

37:22.624 --> 37:25.024
[music]

37:27.663 --> 37:30.131
<i>a cop...</i>

37:35.270 --> 37:37.205
...a friend.

37:37.272 --> 37:41.542
<i>I met Barry when he joined homicide.</i>

37:41.577 --> 37:45.213
And he was so nervous because

37:45.247 --> 37:48.116
parts of the job didn't
really agree with him,

37:48.150 --> 37:50.718
<i>but he didn't let that stand in his way.</i>

37:50.786 --> 37:53.588
<i>He just wanted to be the
best cop that he could be.</i>

37:53.622 --> 37:55.823
<i>He wanted to work harder, be smarter,</i>

37:55.891 --> 37:58.226
<i>try new things, and push himself.</i>

37:58.293 --> 38:01.596
And I admired

38:01.630 --> 38:04.565
the passion that he brought to his work.

38:04.600 --> 38:09.737
I will miss him as my partner.

38:13.842 --> 38:17.945
And I will ... [voice breaking]
and I will miss him as my friend.

38:20.115 --> 38:25.019
<i>But as I was preparing this eulogy,</i>

38:25.054 --> 38:29.190
<i>I realized that I didn't want to
just think about what we've lost.</i>

38:29.224 --> 38:31.859
<i>I wanted to find something
that we could hold on to.</i>

38:31.927 --> 38:35.029
<i>So I started thinking about Barry</i>

38:35.064 --> 38:37.999
and ... and what I
really loved about him.

38:38.033 --> 38:41.169
And ... and one idea
kept coming to mind.

38:45.707 --> 38:48.643
I really loved how he made me laugh.

38:52.881 --> 38:56.717
<i>And I will miss that infectious smile</i>

38:56.785 --> 39:01.625
<i>and the joy that he
brought to every day.</i>

39:03.826 --> 39:08.763
So, in this moment when it
feels like there is none,

39:08.831 --> 39:10.898
here is the good news.

39:10.933 --> 39:12.700
[inhales sharply]

39:20.809 --> 39:23.811
[voice breaking]
Death may have taken Barry,

39:23.846 --> 39:28.316
but it can't take our memories of him.

39:28.383 --> 39:32.987
Those wonderful and perfect

39:33.021 --> 39:36.090
<i>and beautiful memories.</i>

39:37.993 --> 39:40.862
Those, thank god, are ours to keep.

39:50.072 --> 39:54.453
[piano plays "What a wonderful world"]

40:13.028 --> 40:14.996
<i>Yeah, yeah.</i>

40:15.030 --> 40:18.232
[sighs] Maura, I'm gonna be okay.

40:18.300 --> 40:20.134
Yes.

40:20.169 --> 40:23.437
No, no. I'm ... really,
I'm going right to bed.

40:24.907 --> 40:28.009
I know that you would come
over and stay with me, yes.

40:28.043 --> 40:30.778
You know you're a good friend, right?

40:31.013 --> 40:34.015
Okay. I'll see you tomorrow.

40:34.049 --> 40:35.049
[cellphone beeps]

40:37.121 --> 40:40.947
[music]

40:46.798 --> 40:51.131
<i>"Couldn't be better here,
but I miss you anyway.  Barry."</i>

40:52.401 --> 40:56.170
[sniffles]

41:03.178 --> 41:06.414
[crying]

